{"text": " What if a big asteroid were headed for Earth? What are the three most realistic ways we could stop it? So in 2013, the United Nations created a special group of space agencies to decide between the options in exactly this situation. Option one, you do nothing. There's always a chance it'll miss you, but maybe not. So option two, you smash a spacecraft into it to change its course just enough that it misses Earth. We've tested this in real life. In 2022, NASA deliberately slammed a spacecraft the size of a vending machine into an asteroid the size of a few city blocks, and it worked. It significantly changed the asteroid's path. 25 times more than they expected, and their blueprints for an even bigger one. And now, option three, you nuke the asteroid. But not to explode it, because that would probably just make a bunch of dangerous fragments that might get pulled back together by gravity and hit us anyway. So instead, the idea is to nuke just one side of it, vaporizing part of its surface, turning the asteroid into a rocket, pushing it in the opposite direction. And there are two more wild options here as well. To see those, watch our longer video with Mark Rober. Or so follow along.", "segments": [{"id": 0, "seek": 0, "start": 0.0, "end": 2.72, "text": " What if a big asteroid were headed for Earth?", "tokens": [50364, 708, 498, 257, 955, 33833, 645, 12798, 337, 4755, 30, 50500], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.09598055100978765, "compression_ratio": 1.5795795795795795, "no_speech_prob": 0.0028451927937567234}, {"id": 1, "seek": 0, "start": 2.72, "end": 5.6000000000000005, "text": " What are the three most realistic ways we could stop it?", "tokens": [50500, 708, 366, 264, 1045, 881, 12465, 2098, 321, 727, 1590, 309, 30, 50644], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.09598055100978765, "compression_ratio": 1.5795795795795795, "no_speech_prob": 0.0028451927937567234}, {"id": 2, "seek": 0, "start": 5.6000000000000005, "end": 9.44, "text": " So in 2013,